#范文[The line graph shows the proportion of urban population in four Southeast Asian countries—Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, and Indonesia—from 1970 to 2020, with projections to 2040.

Overall, urbanisation increased in all four nations, but at markedly different rates. Malaysia experienced the most rapid and consistent growth, rising from 30% in 1970 to 75% in 2020, and is forecast to reach 85% by 2040—the highest among the group.

In contrast, the Philippines began at a relatively high level (33%) but saw a decline between 1990 and 2010, falling to 42%. By 2020, it had recovered slightly to 45%, and is expected to reach just 55% by 2040.

Thailand and Indonesia started with low urban shares (18% and 14% respectively). While Thailand’s growth was modest (30% in 2020), Indonesia’s rose sharply to 50% by 2000—surpassing Thailand—and is projected to hit 62% by 2040.]

